---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const componentNames = `.product-card
.site-header
.filter-panel`;

const childSelectors = `.product-card > .title
.product-card > .price
.site-header > .logo
.filter-panel > .actions`;

const modifierAndStateClasses = `.product-card--featured
.product-card--compact
.is_active
.has_error`;

const comparisonExample = `/* BEM-style element naming */
.product-card__title {}
.product-card__price {}

/* LSCSS-style contextual child selectors */
.product-card > .title {}
.product-card > .price {}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Naming"
    description="Naming conventions used in Layered Semantic CSS, including semantic components, RSCSS-style child selectors, BEM-style modifiers, and explicit state classes."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Naming</p>

        <h1>
            Semantic naming
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            LSCSS prefers readable semantic names over tightly coupled structural
            naming. Component names describe what something is. Child selectors
            stay short because the parent component gives them context.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Naming sections">
        <a href="#influences">Influences</a>
        <a href="#components">Components</a>
        <a href="#child-selectors">Child selectors</a>
        <a href="#modifiers-and-state">Modifiers and state</a>
        <a href="#comparison">Comparison</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="influences" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Methodology influences
        </h2>

        <p>
            LSCSS is not pretending CSS history started from scratch. It borrows
            useful ideas from existing methodologies, then adapts them for
            modern CSS features, cascade layers, and simpler markup.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>RSCSS-style selectors influence the use of short child classes scoped by the parent component.</li>
            <li>BEM-style modifier classes influence the use of explicit component variants.</li>
            <li>ITCSS influences the focus on ordered layers and predictable specificity.</li>
            <li>Modern CSS adds tools such as :where(), :has(), nesting, @scope, and container queries.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="components" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Components
        </h2>

        <p>
            Component names should be semantic and readable. They should describe
            the role of the component, not its current visual treatment.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={componentNames} />
    </section>

    <section id="child-selectors" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Child selectors
        </h2>

        <p>
            LSCSS uses short child classes inside the context of a parent
            component. This borrows from the RSCSS preference for simple element
            names such as <code>.title</code>, <code>.content</code>, and
            <code>.actions</code>, scoped by the parent selector.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={childSelectors} />

        <p>
            This keeps HTML easier to read while still making ownership clear in
            the CSS.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="modifiers-and-state" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Modifiers and state
        </h2>

        <p>
            LSCSS keeps the useful BEM idea of explicit modifiers for component
            variants. State classes remain separate because temporary UI state is
            not the same thing as a reusable component variant.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={modifierAndStateClasses} />
    </section>

    <section id="comparison" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            BEM-style elements vs contextual child selectors
        </h2>

        <p>
            BEM encodes the parent-child relationship into the class name.
            LSCSS usually keeps that relationship in the selector instead.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={comparisonExample} />

        <p>
            Neither approach is magic. LSCSS chooses the shorter form because
            the parent component already provides the context and cascade layers
            help control the wider architecture.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
